Out[14]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f464c27fcf8>

The mean value of homes of 540,088 is greater than the median of 450,000. This is an indication that the response variable is positively skewed (Skewness: 4.024069). When this happens, regressing the log of price usually provides a better fitting, compared to the original price.

Majority of the houses are priced below $2000000.

In [15]:
# log the price
house["price"] = np.log(house["price"])
# get the mean for the log price
m=house.price.mean()
# get the standard deviation of the log price
std=house.price.std()

#scaling to get a log normal distribution
house.price = (house.price - m) / std
sns.distplot(house.price)

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.20)

Gradient boosting and random forest seem to have roughly the same test R-square score. However, gradient forest has a significantly smaller overfitting effect than random forest. Moreover, I have already tried random forest in CA1, there is no fun in repeating the same thing. Hence I choose gradient boosting for hyperparameter tunning and model retraining.

learning_rate¶

In [50]:
portion = np.arange(0.01, 1 ,0.05)

scores = pd.DataFrame(index=portion, columns=['train','test'])

for p in portion:
    GBest = GradientBoostingRegressor(learning_rate=p)
    GBest.fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    y_train_pred = GBest.predict(X_train)
    y_test_pred = GBest.predict(X_test)
    scores.loc[p,'train'] = r2_score(y_train,y_train_pred)
    scores.loc[p,'test'] = r2_score(y_test,y_test_pred)
scores.plot()

Final results¶

Retrain model¶

In [47]:
# set the hyperparameter according to the highest test R2 score
#use max_features='sqrt' to reduce overfitting of my model
#use loss='huber' to be more tolerant to outliers. 
GBest = GradientBoostingRegressor(n_estimators=600, learning_rate=0.1, max_features='sqrt',min_samples_leaf=15, min_samples_split=10, loss='huber')
GBest.fit(X_train,y_train)
pred1 = GBest.predict(X_train)
pred2 = GBest.predict(X_test)
new_amse_GBest = format(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train,pred1)),'.3f')
new_bmse_GBest = format(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test,pred2)),'.3f')
new_ar2_GBest = format(r2_score(y_train,pred1),'.3f')
new_br2_GBest = format(r2_score(y_test,pred2),'.3f')

Conclusion¶

  • Q: How is your prediction task defined? And what is the meaning of the output variable?
  • A: The task is to predict the selling price of houses in King's county based on their relevent supplementary information. The output variable is the price prediction.

  • Q:How do you represent your data as features?
  • A: I use bar graphs,distplot,scatter diagram, distribution curve, histogram, factorplot, 3Dplot, ggplot.

  • Q:Did you process the features in any way?
  • A: I derived the age and year of sale from the date column.

  • Q:Did you bring in any additional sources of data?
  • A: Nope

  • Q:How did you select which learning algorithms to use?
  • A: I evaluate based on R-square score and Mean Squared Error.

  • Q:Did you try to tune the hyperparameters of the learning algorithm, and in that case how?
  • A: I plot of graph show how r2 score varies with each hyperparameter, and then picked the value with the highest test r2 score. I also adjust some hyperparameter based on the outliers.

  • Q:How do you evaluate the quality of your system?
  • A: I compare the predicted price with the actual price using r2 score and mse. Then checked the diffence between train score and test score to prevent overfitting.

  • Q:How well does your system compare to a stupid baseline?
  • A: Extremely well in all aspects.Please refer to 6.1: 'Comparison' to check the different score or each alorithm and the stupid baseline.

  • Q:Can you say anything about the errors that the system makes?
  • A: The system takes very long to load, it is taking in a lot of outliers into its train model.

  • Q:Is it possible to say something about which features the model considers important?
  • A: Zipcode is the most important feature. 'condition' and 'bathrooms' are also very important. Please refer to 6.2: 'Feature importance' for the full list.
